To: \>Van\\
Subject: \>TScat and derivatives\\
From: \>Van Snyder\\
\end{tabbing}

\parindent 0pt \parskip 10pt
\vspace{-20pt}

We calculate $T_\text{scat}$ by propagating a ray from space through a sample
atmosphere to a specified point $s$.  The points on that ray are called $r$ in
the sequel.

At $s$ we have the phase function $P(\theta)$, $\frac{\partial
P(\theta)}{\partial x_s}$, radiance $I$ resulting from radiative transfer along
the ray to $s$, $\frac{\partial I}{\partial x_s}$,
and $\frac{\partial I}{\partial x_r}$, where $x$ is temperature, IWC, or a
mixing ratio. $T_\text{scat}$ is defined as

\begin{equation*}
T_\text{scat} = \int_{-\pi}^\pi P(\theta) I(\theta) \, \text{d}\theta
\end{equation*}

where $\theta$ is the angle between the incident ray and the scattered ray that
originates at $s$.

From this

\begin{equation*}
\frac{\partial T_\text{scat}}{\partial x_s} =
 \int_{-\pi}^\pi
  \left[ \frac{\partial P(\theta)}{\partial x_s} I +
         P(\theta) \frac{\partial I}{\partial x_s} \right]
  \, \text{d} \theta
\end{equation*}

and

\begin{equation*}
\frac{\partial T_\text{scat}}{\partial x_r} =
 \int_{-\pi}^\pi 
  \left [ \frac{\partial P(\theta)}{\partial x_r} I +
          P(\theta) \frac{\partial I}{\partial x_r} \right]
  \, \text{d} \theta =
 \int_{-\pi}^\pi P(\theta) \frac{\partial I}{\partial x_r} \, \text{d} \theta\,.
\end{equation*}

